how reading poetic form from a historical perspective yields fresh insights into verse's complexities.Rush explores how early modern poets imagined rhyme as a band or fetter, comparing it to the bonds linking individuals to political, social, and religious communities. She considers how Edmund Spenser's sonnet rhymes stood as emblems of voluntary confinement, how John Donne's revival of the Chaucerian couplet signaled sexual and political radicalism, and how Ben Jonson's verse charted a middle way between licentious Elizabethan couplet poets and slavish sonneteers. Rush then looks at why the royalist poets embraced the prerational charms of rhyme, and how Milton spent his career reckoning with rhyme's allures.Examining a poetic feature that sits between sound and sense, liberty and measure, The Fetters of Rhyme elucidates early modern efforts to negotiate these forces in verse making and reading.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCouplets, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish languagexRhyme. 0aEnglish poetryyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aPoetics. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh  aAbraham Cowley.  aAmoretti.  aDavid Caplan.  aDonald Wesling.  aDonnean couplet.  aElizabethan.  aEnglish Civil War.  aInns of Court.  aKatherine Philips.  aMilton and the Burden of Freedom.  aMilton and the Poetics of Freedom.  aPoetics.  aRenaissance.  aRhyme's Challenge.  aRobert Herrick.  aSusanne Woods.  aThe Chances of Rhyme.  aWarren Chernaik.  aanalogy.  abonds of the heart.  ahistory of liberalism.  ahistory of the lyric.  aiambic pentameter.  alove's bands.  alyric.  ameasure.  amodern song.  amodern verse.  apoetic sublimity.  aprosody.  arhetorical studies.  arhyme's chime.  aseventeenth-century.  averse culture.08iTitle is